Analysis of Drinking Water Types, Qualities, and Factors

CMSC320 Final Tutorial

By: Isabella Battish, Janet Choi, Sarah Hwang

Link to Data

Drinking water infrastructure is critical to a safe and healthy population. Every living being needs safe and clean drinking water, in fact, it's one of the UN's Sustainable Development goals. While, the U.S. does have better drinking water quality and infrastructure compared to many places, the quality of drinking water is not equal everywhere in the U.S. The U.S. has old infrastructure and repairs and maintenance are lagging, especially in places with limited public spending. The older pipes can corrode and contaminate drinking water with materials we don't want to drink such as lead. The most famous recent (and ongoing) case of this is in Flint, Michigan where city employees tried to cut costs on water allowing 'hard' (mineral dense) water from the Flint River enter old pipes and corrode them so that they contaminated the drinking water with lead. Another famous example is from West Virginia where tap water was capable of catching on fire after a chemical that is used to clean coal was spilled into a nearby river. Other places that have had issues with water include Jackson, Mississippe, NYC, Baltimore, MD, and others. These cases show just how critical it is that we ensure our water quality and the infrastructure that brings us our water is up to date and properly functioning.

In this tutorial, we will walk you through the Data Science Pipeline.

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Processing
  3. Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization
  4. Anaylysis and Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning
  5. Insight and Policy Decision.

We hope that this walkthrough will show insights on the U.S. drinking water infrastructure, while also shedding light on potential risk areas in drinking water.

Throughout this tutorial we will analyze a variety of factors, and how they pertain to drinking water.

To learn more about drinking water crises in the U.S. please visit these links:

The first step in the Data Science pipeline is Data Collection. Data Collection can mean scraping data from a website using the Python BeautifulSoup library, using http requests to get data from a website, or using Pandas to read in a csv file into a data frame. In this project we will be reading in a csv file. The data in the csv file can be found at https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/DFB6NG, download the file called MDWD.tab. The dataset is also called the Municipal Drinking Water Database (MDWD) and uses data from the Census and the EPA to help researchers interested in learning more about drinking water and factors that influence it. All we have to do is import all of our necessary imports for the tutorial, and run pd.read_csv. We call df.head() to show that we were successful in collecting our data.

The second step in the Data Science pipeline is Data Processing. In the data processing stage we 'clean' our data so it is an easy to understand and workable format. Our data has A LOT of columns, and we will not be using the data in all of those columns. To get rid of many of the columns we drop/delete all of the columns where financial expenses are 'nonadjusted'. The nonadjusted part means that it's the cost of something but not changed to reflect inflation. We only want the adjusted expenditures. Now our data is a little bit easier to read.

For starters, we are curious if there's a relationship between where a municipalities drinking water is sourced and what percentage of the area voted for Hillary Clinton in the 2016 election.

             data=df_2016)
Out[ ]:
<Axes: xlabel='PRIMARY_SOURCE_CODE', ylabel='demshare_pres_2016'>

Interesting, our results don't show any relationship between the source of the water and the percentage of votes for the Democratic presidential candidate in 2016. For more context on what the source codes mean

  • SWP= Purchased Surface Water
  • SW= Surface Water
  • GW= Ground Water
  • GWP= Purchased Ground Water
  • GU= Ground Water Influenced by Surface Water
  • GUP= Purchased Ground Water Influenced by Surface Water

Surface water is water that is not underground, examples of this include rivers and reservoirs. While most places with surface water drinking sources are safe because the water is treated, surface water is most likely to be contaminated by external means. For example, in West Virginia a chemical spill into their river is what caused the drinking water to be contaminated, and in Flint, Michigan the Flint River's corrosiveness compared to ground water is what caused lead from the pipes to enter the drinking water supply.

Ground water is water from deep underground in deep wells and aquifers. The biggest and most famous aquifer in the U.S. is the Ogallala Aquifer. The Ogallala Aquifer runs underneath most of the Midwest and supplies water for the farms all over the place there. Unfortunately, the water supply is running out due to overusage. To learn more follow this link

Ground water influenced by surface water means that the source of the water is groundwater but it's close enough to the surface to be influenced by surface water recharge, an example of this is springs and shallow wells and aquafers. This can lead to contaminants that aren't typically found in groundwater could be found in GU or GUP. To learn more about GU follow this link.

There is also only one observation in 2016 that used GUP, let's explore that further. Based on the codeblock below, it looks like South Sioux City, Nebraska is the only municipality with purchased Ground Water Influenced by Surface Water.

Next is step 4 of the Data Science Pipeline: Analysis and Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning. In machine learning, analysis, and hypothesis testing we will use math and different model types to use our data to predict what the value of some other data might be. We will be using various variables related to drinking water with different factors about a municipality to predict as well. We will be using three different machine learning models to explore some different questions and areas of interest in drinking water infrastructure.The models we'll be using is Linear Regression with Gradient Descent, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN).

So we do some Ordinary Least Squares (OLS). OLS is a regression model that will help us establish a relationship between our variables better and get some more descriptive statistics. So we run an OLS model with our dependent variable (what we're predicting) as Water Utility Revenue and our independent variables (what we're basing our prediction on) as Population, Health Expenditures, Total Outstanding Debt, and Percent of Population in Poverty.

In [ ]:
# seeing the summary stats from the regression model

# Gradient Descent (Lecture Code)

def grad_descent_ridge(X,y,T,alpha,lam):
    m, n = X.shape
    theta = np.zeros(n)
    #theta = np.array([0.002050, 0.327121, 0.340441, 0.333236, -0.000008])
    f = np.zeros(T)

    for i in range(T):
        f[i] = 0.5*np.linalg.norm(X.dot(theta)-y)**2 #
        #g = np.transpose(X).dot(X.dot(theta)-y)
        g = X.T @ ((X @ theta) - y)
        theta = theta*(1-((alpha*lam)/m)) - (alpha/m)*g
        #lst.append(theta)
    return(theta,f)

We'll also be running a Support Vector Machine (SVM) to help us predict the type of water source a place has based on factors such as Total Debt Outstanding, Health Total Expenditure, Water Utility Revenue, and Health Violations. SVMs allow us to predict a classification or category by fitting a hyperplane to split all the points between each category. To make our analysis easier, I will recode GW or GWP as 1 and everything else as 0.
